  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong and widespread consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through complex sequences of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is universally condemned and criminalized because it enables the integration of proceeds from illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and organized crime, into the legitimate financial system.\n\nMost countries around the world have implemented laws and regulations to combat money laundering, and many adhere to international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which is the global money laundering and terrorist financing watchdog. The FATF sets international standards to combat money laundering and the financing of terrorism, and its recommendations are widely adopted by member countries.\n\nIn the United States, for example, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act include provisions specifically aimed at preventing and detecting money laundering. Similarly, the European Union has its own set of directives, such as the Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD), which member states are required to implement into their national laws.\n\nOverall, the legal frameworks and international cooperation established to combat money laundering reflect the global consensus that it is a serious crime that undermines the integrity of financial systems and contributes to broader societal harms.",
